summary:
Bu çalışma dört varsayım etrafında kurulmuştur:
-Her şeye rağmen Osmanlı Devleti'nin son 14 yılı içinde bile ulema hala devlette  önemli bir ağırlığa sahiptir; 
- Kriz içinde bulunan ulema ilk defa II. Meşrutiyet idaresinde bu krizin analizini yapabilmiştir; 
- Ulema İstiklal Savaşı içinde Milliyetçi harekete müstesna bir yardım sağlamıştır; 
 - Nihayet Cumhuriyet devrinde yapılan reformlara bir kısım ulema meşruiyyet kazandırmakla hala vazgeçilmez bir unsur olduğunu göstermiştir.

This work by Shehu Uthman ibn Fuduye` (Dan Fodio) is arguably one of his most important works. In it he addresses all the issues of Iman, Islam and Ihsan from the perspective of the prophetic traditions. You can actually describe this work as a collection of prophetic traditions on beliefs, worship and social transactions. He seals the text with a chapter on Jihaad which I beleive is extremely relevant today. He describes the religion as it is and is not apologetic about the issue of military struggle and the need for self determination.
The Shehu divided the Sawq’l-Umma into twelve books after its introduction, in which he cited 3 prophetic traditions. They are: 
1 the Book of Belief in which he cited 15 prophetic traditions; 
2 the Book of Purification in which he cited 21 prophetic traditions; 
3 the Book of Menstruation in which he cited 9 prophetic traditions; 
4 the Book of Tayammamu in which he cited 7 prophetic traditions, 
5 the Book of Prayer in which he cited 60 prophetic traditions; 
6 the Book of Juma`a in which he cited 7 prophetic traditions; 
7 the Book of Prayers of Fear, the Two Eid, Rain and Eclipse in which he cited 17 prophetic traditions; 
8 the Book of the Deceased in which he cited 8 prophetic traditions;
9 the Book of Obligatory Alms in which he cited 8 prophetic traditions; 
10 the Book of Fasting in which he cited 10 prophetic traditions; 
11 the Book of Pilgrimage in which he cited 29 prophetic traditions; and finally 
12 the Book of Jihaad in which he cited 38 prophetic traditions. 
The Shehu, may the mercy of Allah be upon him said: “The expressions from the narrations of al-Bukhari are more prominent in this book than those of Muslim, even though both contribute to what is largely desired in meaning.” He cited in these books 232 prophetic traditions: 207 from the Saheeh of al-Bukhari; and 23 from the Saheeh of Muslim. Although he said that he only cited from the two Saheeh collections, however he made an exception in that in two prophetic traditions. The first being what he narrated in the section on the superogatory prayers regarding the four raka`at performed before the `asr prayer, where he said: “I have not come across the evidence of four rak`ats before the `asr prayer in the two Saheeh collections.  However it has been related by an-Nisaa’i from a tradition on Ali ibn Abi Taalib, may Allah ennoble his face.” The second exception is what he narrated in the Book of the obligatory alms where he said: “I have not come across the amount to be paid for cattle in the two Saheeh collections.” He then cited a prophetic tradition regarding this from the narrations of at-Tirmidhi on the authority of Mu`adh.
The Sawq’l-Umma composed in 1794 CE (1208 AH)  is a reference book, for the schools of thought of the mujtahiduun in their independent judgments and legal extractions. One of my teachers once said to me: “The book Sawq’l-Umma with regard to the individual obligations is similar to the al-Muwatta of Imam Malik ibn Anas, and is a reference for the Risaalat of Ibn Abi Zayd or the al-Mukhtasar of Khalil ibn Is’haq.” This is because he established in it the soundest narrations from the Lawgiver, may Allah bless him and grant him peace based upon the arrangement of these above mentioned books. It is also a compendium of the prophetic traditions like the Buluugh’l-Maraam, the al-`Umdat and the al-Muntaqa.
